{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "02 — Goroutines, Channels & Select",
  "description": "Go's signature feature: lightweight concurrency through goroutines and channels. This tour traces three real patterns in Balaur: the Ollama manager's process lifecycle, the streaming HTTP client, and the chat handler's chunked flush loop.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/ollama/manager.go",
      "line": 32,
      "title": "2.1 — Manager: struct with a mutex",
      "description": "```go\ntype Manager struct {\n    mu sync.Mutex\n\n    // lifecycle\n    dataDir string\n    cmd     *exec.Cmd\n    spawned bool\n    tail    *ringBuffer\n\n    // single-slot pull\n    cancel   context.CancelFunc\n    progress PullSnapshot\n    onDone   func(tag string)\n}\n```\n\n`sync.Mutex` is Go's mutual exclusion lock. The lowercase fields are unexported — callers outside the `ollama` package can't access them. They're internal implementation detail.\n\nThe mutex is needed because `EnsureRunning`, `Stop`, and `Pull` may be called concurrently: the HTTP handler for a chat request calls `EnsureRunning` on the first model call, while the shutdown hook calls `Stop`. Without a mutex, both could see and modify `cmd` at the same time — a data race that the Go race detector would catch.\n\nThe canonical Go mutex pattern: **lock immediately, defer unlock immediately** so you can never forget to unlock even if you add early returns later."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/ollama/manager.go",
      "line": 55,
      "title": "2.2 — EnsureRunning: the guarded hot path",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (m *Manager) EnsureRunning(ctx context.Context) error {\n    a := m.apiClient()\n    if a.up(ctx) {\n        return nil\n    }\n    return m.spawn(ctx)\n}\n```\n\nThis is the idiomatic Go \"check-then-act\" pattern. `EnsureRunning` first probes the Ollama API (`GET /api/tags`) — if another process already has Ollama running, we adopt it for free. Only if Ollama is unreachable do we spawn our own.\n\nNote: `ctx` propagates cancellation — if the caller times out while Ollama is loading, `spawn` returns `ctx.Err()`."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/ollama/manager.go",
      "line": 77,
      "title": "2.3 — spawn: launching the subprocess",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (m *Manager) spawn(ctx context.Context) error {\n    m.mu.Lock()\n    if m.cmd != nil {\n        m.mu.Unlock()\n        return nil\n    }\n    ...\n    if err := cmd.Start(); err != nil {\n        m.mu.Unlock()\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"starting ollama serve: %w\", err)\n    }\n    m.cmd = cmd\n    m.spawned = true\n    m.mu.Unlock() // release before the readiness poll\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n`cmd.Start()` launches `ollama serve` as a child process and returns immediately — the process runs in the background. Unlike `cmd.Run()`, it does not wait for the command to finish.\n\nThe mutex is released **before** the readiness poll loop. Why? Holding the lock during a blocking network poll would freeze every other goroutine trying to call `Snapshot`, `Pull`, or `Cancel`. Release early, then poll without a lock.\n\n`m.spawned = true` remembers that **Balaur started this process** — `Stop` only kills a process Balaur owns, not an externally managed Ollama instance."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/ollama/manager.go",
      "line": 100,
      "title": "2.4 — spawn: select for two-way cancellation",
      "description": "```go\ndeadline := time.Now().Add(maxLoad)\nfor time.Now().Before(deadline) {\n    if a.up(ctx) {\n        return nil\n    }\n    select {\n    case <-time.After(300 * time.Millisecond):\n    case <-ctx.Done():\n        return ctx.Err()\n    }\n}\nreturn fmt.Errorf(\"ollama serve did not become ready in %s\\n%s\", maxLoad, tail.String())\n```\n\n`select` is Go's **switch-for-channels**: it waits until one of the listed cases is ready, then executes exactly that case. If multiple are ready simultaneously, it picks one at random.\n\nThis `select` (no `default`) is a **blocking sleep** with cancellation: wait 300ms, but wake immediately if the context is cancelled. Without the `ctx.Done()` case, a cancelled HTTP request would leave the goroutine stuck sleeping until the deadline expires.\n\nThis is the canonical Go pattern for a poll loop that must be interruptible — you will see it in every production Go networking codebase."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 130,
      "title": "2.5 — ChatStream: goroutine + buffered channel",
      "description": "```go\nch := make(chan Chunk, 8)\ngo func() {\n    defer close(ch)\n    defer resp.Body.Close()\n    ...\n}()\nreturn ch, nil\n```\n\n`make(chan Chunk, 8)` creates a **buffered channel** with capacity 8: up to 8 `Chunk` values can sit in the pipe before a send blocks. Why buffered? Without a buffer, every `ch <- chunk` would block until the caller reads. A small buffer lets the goroutine run slightly ahead of the reader — useful when the model produces tokens faster than the HTTP handler can flush them.\n\n`ChatStream` returns `ch` immediately — the goroutine is still running in the background. The caller gets a channel they can read from as tokens arrive.\n\n`defer close(ch)` is the critical safety guarantee: **when the goroutine exits (for any reason), the channel closes**. Anything doing `for chunk := range ch` will exit the loop when the channel closes. Without this, the range loop would wait forever.\n\nThe extra `defer resp.Body.Close()` cleans up the HTTP response body. In Go, HTTP response bodies must be explicitly closed or they leak a connection."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 138,
      "title": "2.6 — SSE line-by-line parsing inside the goroutine",
      "description": "```go\nsc := bufio.NewScanner(resp.Body)\nsc.Buffer(make([]byte, 0, 64*1024), 4*1024*1024)\nfor sc.Scan() {\n    line := strings.TrimSpace(sc.Text())\n    if !strings.HasPrefix(line, \"data:\") {\n        continue\n    }\n    data := strings.TrimSpace(strings.TrimPrefix(line, \"data:\"))\n    if data == \"[DONE]\" {\n        break\n    }\n    ...\n```\n\nServer-Sent Events (SSE) is a text protocol: the server sends lines like `data: {\"choices\":[...]}` and a `data: [DONE]` at the end. `bufio.NewScanner` reads the response body line by line.\n\n`sc.Buffer(...)` sets a larger internal buffer — the default 64KB is too small for responses with long tool-call argument strings.\n\nThis is the only place in Balaur that does raw HTTP/SSE parsing. Everything else talks to clean Go types. Once tokens are extracted and sent into `ch`, the agent loop consumes them the same way regardless of whether the underlying client is local or remote — the channel is the abstraction boundary."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 170,
      "title": "2.7 — Select for cancellation (the most important pattern)",
      "description": "```go\nselect {\ncase ch <- Chunk{Content: d.Content, Reasoning: d.Reasoning}:\ncase <-ctx.Done():\n    ch <- Chunk{Err: ctx.Err()}\n    return\n}\n```\n\n`select` with two cases:\n- Try to send a chunk into `ch`. If the reader is keeping up, this case fires.\n- If the context was cancelled (HTTP request closed, user navigated away, timeout hit), `ctx.Done()` closes, this case fires instead — we send an error chunk and exit the goroutine.\n\nWithout `select`, a cancelled context would leave the goroutine blocked on `ch <-` forever (if nobody is reading), leaking memory until the process dies.\n\nThis pattern appears in both `openai.go` (HTTP streaming) and `internal/ollama/manager.go` (`spawn` poll loop). It is the canonical Go cancellation idiom — you will see it in every production Go networking codebase."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/web/chat.go",
      "line": 67,
      "title": "2.8 — The HTTP flush pattern (streaming HTML)",
      "description": "```go\nw := e.Response\nw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"text/html; charset=utf-8\")\nflusher, _ := w.(http.Flusher)\nflush := func() {\n    if flusher != nil {\n        flusher.Flush()\n    }\n}\n```\n\nHTMX chat streaming uses **chunked HTTP responses**: the handler keeps the connection open and flushes HTML fragments as the model produces tokens. The browser (via HTMX's `hx-swap beforeend`) appends each fragment to the DOM without a full page load.\n\n`w.(http.Flusher)` is a **type assertion**: it checks whether the underlying `ResponseWriter` implements `http.Flusher` — the optional interface that exposes `Flush()`. Not all response writers support it (e.g., test recorders don't), so the two-value form `_, ok` is used and a nil check is kept.\n\nEach time the agent loop emits a `text` event, `chat.go` writes escaped HTML and calls `flush()` — the browser receives the token immediately rather than waiting for the response to end.\n\n**The data flow:**\n```\nmodel (Ollama)     → SSE chunks over HTTP\n                       ↓\nopenai.go goroutine → ch (chan Chunk)\n                       ↓\nagent.Loop         → emit(Event{Kind:\"text\", Text:...})\n                       ↓\nchat.go emitEv     → fmt.Fprint(w, ...) + flush()\n                       ↓\nbrowser            → HTMX appends to #chat\n```\nThree goroutine boundaries, one channel, one HTTP flush loop — the whole streaming pipeline."
    }
  ]
}
